title: Porte des Enfants du Rhône
description: Cette dernière fait l'objet d'un concours lancé en 1898, remporté par Charles Meysson. La porte est réalisée par l'entreprise lyonnaise Jean Bernard. Mesurant trente-deux mètres de longueur, la grille comporte deux pylônes en pierre de Villeboy. La porte centrale mesure onze mètres de hauteur. L'ensemble de la porte pèse onze tonnes. (wikipédia)

title: Rue Juiverie
description: Forced out in the 14C the Jews were replaced by Italian bankers who built sumptuous houses, like the hôtel Paterin (also called «maison Henri IV») at No. 4, the hôtel Bullioud with Philibert Delorme gallery (n° 8), Antoine Groslier de Servières's house (No. 10), the dwelling at No. 20, the Baronat house (No. 22), the Dugas house (au No. 23). On the corner, where this street meets with la place Saint-Paul, you will see the palais de la Miniature (Miniature Palace) (viamichelin.com)

Maison Thomassin
description:
Quelques éléments de cette maison datent de 1298. Il s'agit de l'une des anciennes maison d'habitation de Lyon. Sa façade fut reconstruite en 1493 dans un style gothique à l'initiative de Claude Thomassin, riche notable et commerçant lyonnais.

title: Rue Saint-Jean - Place du Change
description: The main shopping street in Old Lyon still has many beautiful dwellings such as the hôtel de la Chamarerie (n° 37) with a Flamboyant façade, the house of the advocates (rue Bombarde), and the houses at 58, 52, 50, 42 and 36. No. 54 looks on to Old Lyon's longest traboule linking five courtyards near rue du Boeuf. Hôtel Laurencin at No. 24 and the beautiful interior courtyard at No. 28 are also worth seeing. Taverns and craft shops add sparkle to this pedestrian area. (viamichelin.com)

title: Rue du Boeuf
description: Here you will see beautiful Renaissance buildings, some of which have become hotels, such as the Cour des Loges at No. 6; a beautiful three-storey U-shaped courtyard. You will also see the maison du Crible at No. 16, with its lavish doorway; the Pink Tower and its two stacked courtyards, in the bar you will notice two walls of a real tennis court of Old Lyon. At No. 19, la maison de l'Outarde d'Or has a stone ensign in sculpted stone and a court with two turrets. (viamichelin.com)
